# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-vpn
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In computing, **Internet Protocol Security** (**IPsec**) is a secure network protocol suite that authenticates and encrypts packets of data to provide secure encrypted communication between two computers over an Internet Protocol network.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] It is used in virtual private networks (VPNs).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec includes protocols for establishing mutual authentication between agents at the beginning of a session and negotiation of cryptographic keys to use during the session.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec can protect data flows between a pair of hosts (*host-to-host*), between a pair of security gateways (*network-to-network*), or between a security gateway and a host (*network-to-host*).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec uses cryptographic security services to protect communications over Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] It supports network-level peer authentication, data origin authentication, data integrity, data confidentiality (encryption), and protection from replay attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Starting in the early 1970s, the Advanced Research Projects Agency sponsored a series of experimental ARPANET encryption devices, at first for native ARPANET packet encryption and subsequently for TCP/IP packet encryption; some of these were certified and fielded.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] From 1986 to 1991, the NSA sponsored the development of security protocols for the Internet under its Secure Data Network Systems (SDNS) program.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This brought together various vendors including Motorola who produced a network encryption device in 1988.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The work was openly published from about 1988 by NIST and, of these, *Security Protocol at Layer 3* (SP3) would eventually morph into the ISO standard Network Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In 1992, the US Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) was funded by DARPA CSTO to implement IPv6 and to research and implement IP encryption in 4.4 BSD, supporting both SPARC and x86 CPU architectures.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] DARPA made its implementation freely available via MIT.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Under NRL's DARPA-funded research effort, NRL developed the IETF standards-track specifications (RFC 1825 through RFC 1827) for IPsec.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] NRL's IPsec implementation was described in their paper in the 1996 USENIX Conference Proceedings.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] NRL's open-source IPsec implementation was made available online by MIT and became the basis for most initial commercial implementations.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed the IP Security Working Group in 1992 to standardize openly specified security extensions to IP, called *IPsec*.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The NRL developed standards were published by the IETF as RFC 1825 through RFC 1827.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The initial IPv4 suite was developed with few security provisions.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] As a part of the IPv4 enhancement, IPsec is a layer 3 OSI model or internet layer end-to-end security scheme.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The Security Authentication Header (AH) was developed at the US Naval Research Laboratory in the early 1990s and is derived in part from previous IETF standards' work for authentication of the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) version 2.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Authentication Header (AH) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] AH ensures connectionless integrity by using a hash function and a secret shared key in the AH algorithm.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] AH also guarantees the data origin by authenticating IP packets.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Optionally a sequence number can protect the IPsec packet's contents against replay attacks, using the sliding window technique and discarding old packets.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] AH operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 51.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Type of the next header, indicating what upper-layer protocol was protected.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] For example, an AH value of 4 equals 3×(32-bit fixed-length AH fields) + 3×(32-bit ICV fields) − 2 and thus an AH value of 4 means 24 octets.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Although the size is measured in 4-octet units, the length of this header needs to be a multiple of 8 octets if carried in an IPv6 packet.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Reserved for future use (all zeroes until then).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] When replay detection is enabled, sequence numbers are never reused, because a new security association must be renegotiated before an attempt to increment the sequence number beyond its maximum value.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The IP Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) was developed at the Naval Research Laboratory starting in 1992 as part of a DARPA-sponsored research project, and was openly published by IETF SIPP Working Group drafted in December 1993 as a security extension for SIPP.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This ESP was originally derived from the US Department of Defense SP3D protocol, rather than being derived from the ISO Network-Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The SP3D protocol specification was published by NIST in the late 1980s, but designed by the Secure Data Network System project of the US Department of Defense.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] It provides origin authenticity through source authentication, data integrity through hash functions and confidentiality through encryption protection for IP packets.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] ESP also supports encryption-only and authentication-only configurations, but using encryption without authentication is strongly discouraged because it is insecure.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Unlike Authentication Header (AH), ESP in transport mode does not provide integrity and authentication for the entire IP packet.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] However, in tunnel mode, where the entire original IP packet is encapsulated with a new packet header added, ESP protection is afforded to the whole inner IP packet (including the inner header) while the outer header (including any outer IPv4 options or IPv6 extension headers) remains unprotected.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] ESP operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 50.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] There is a separate counter kept for every security association.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The protected contents of the original IP packet, including any data used to protect the contents (e.g. an Initialisation Vector for the cryptographic algorithm).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] ) is used for dummy packets, which may be inserted in the stream, and which contents should be discarded.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The IPsec protocols use a security association, where the communicating parties establish shared security attributes such as algorithms and keys.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] As such, IPsec provides a range of options once it has been determined whether AH or ESP is used.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Before exchanging data, the two hosts agree on which symmetric encryption algorithm is used to encrypt the IP packet, for example AES or ChaCha20, and which hash function is used to ensure the integrity of the data, such as BLAKE2 or SHA256.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] These parameters are agreed for the particular session, for which a lifetime must be agreed and a session key.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The algorithm for authentication is also agreed before the data transfer takes place and IPsec supports a range of methods.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Authentication is possible through pre-shared key, where a symmetric key is already in the possession of both hosts, and the hosts send each other hashes of the shared key to prove that they are in possession of the same key.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec also supports public key encryption, where each host has a public and a private key, they exchange their public keys and each host sends the other a nonce encrypted with the other host's public key.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Alternatively if both hosts hold a public key certificate from a certificate authority, this can be used for IPsec authentication.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The security associations of IPsec are established using the Internet Security Association and Key Management Protocol (ISAKMP).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] ISAKMP is implemented by manual configuration with pre-shared secrets, Internet Key Exchange (IKE and IKEv2), Kerberized Internet Negotiation of Keys (KINK), and the use of IPSECKEY DNS records.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] RFC 5386 defines Better-Than-Nothing Security (BTNS) as an unauthenticated mode of IPsec using an extended IKE protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Cremers, and others have used formal methods to identify various anomalies which exist in IKEv1 and also in IKEv2.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] A similar procedure is performed for an incoming packet, where IPsec gathers decryption and verification keys from the security association database.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] For IP multicast a security association is provided for the group, and is duplicated across all authorized receivers of the group.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] There may be more than one security association for a group, using different SPIs, thereby allowing multiple levels and sets of security within a group.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Indeed, each sender can have multiple security associations, allowing authentication, since a receiver can only know that someone knowing the keys sent the data.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Note that the relevant standard does not describe how the association is chosen and duplicated across the group; it is assumed that a responsible party will have made the choice.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] To ensure that the connection between two endpoints has not been interrupted, endpoints exchange keepalive messages at regular intervals, which can also be used to automatically reestablish a tunnel lost due to connection interruption.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Dead Peer Detection (DPD) is a method of detecting a dead Internet Key Exchange (IKE) peer.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The method uses IPsec traffic patterns to minimize the number of messages required to confirm the availability of a peer.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] DPD is used to reclaim the lost resources in case a peer is found dead and it is also used to perform IKE peer failover.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The IPsec protocols AH and ESP can be implemented in a host-to-host transport mode, as well as in a network tunneling mode.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In transport mode, only the payload of the IP packet is usually encrypted or authenticated.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The routing is intact, since the IP header is neither modified nor encrypted; however, when the authentication header is used, the IP addresses cannot be modified by network address translation, as this always invalidates the hash value.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The transport and application layers are always secured by a hash, so they cannot be modified in any way, for example by translating the port numbers.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] A means to encapsulate IPsec messages for NAT traversal (NAT-T) has been defined by RFC documents describing the NAT-T mechanism.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In tunnel mode, the entire IP packet is encrypted and authenticated.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] It is then encapsulated into a new IP packet with a new IP header.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Tunnel mode is used to create virtual private networks for network-to-network communications (e.g. between routers to link sites), host-to-network communications (e.g. remote user access) and host-to-host communications (e.g. private chat).
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The IPsec can be implemented in the IP stack of an operating system.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This method of implementation is done for hosts and security gateways.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Various IPsec capable IP stacks are available from companies, such as HP or IBM.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] An alternative is so called bump-in-the-stack (BITS) implementation, where the operating system source code does not have to be modified.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Here IPsec is installed between the IP stack and the network drivers.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This way operating systems can be retrofitted with IPsec.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This method of implementation is also used for both hosts and gateways.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] However, when retrofitting IPsec the encapsulation of IP packets may cause problems for the automatic path MTU discovery, where the maximum transmission unit (MTU) size on the network path between two IP hosts is established.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] If a host or gateway has a separate cryptoprocessor, which is common in the military and can also be found in commercial systems, a so-called bump-in-the-wire (BITW) implementation of IPsec is possible.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] When IPsec is implemented in the kernel, the key management and ISAKMP/IKE negotiation is carried out from user space.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The NRL-developed and openly specified "PF_KEY Key Management API, Version 2" is often used to enable the application-space key management application to update the IPsec security associations stored within the kernel-space IPsec implementation.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Existing IPsec implementations usually include ESP, AH, and IKE version 2.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Existing IPsec implementations on Unix-like operating systems, for example, Solaris or Linux, usually include PF_KEY version 2.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Embedded IPsec can be used to ensure the secure communication among applications running over constrained resource systems with a small overhead.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec was developed in conjunction with IPv6 and was originally required to be supported by all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec is also optional for IPv4 implementations.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec is most commonly used to secure IPv4 traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] IPsec protocols were originally defined in RFC 1825 through RFC 1829, which were published in 1995.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In 1998, these documents were superseded by RFC 2401 and RFC 2412 with a few incompatible engineering details, although they were conceptually identical.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In addition, a mutual authentication and key exchange protocol Internet Key Exchange (IKE) was defined to create and manage security associations.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In December 2005, new standards were defined in RFC 4301 and RFC 4309 which are largely a superset of the previous editions with a second version of the Internet Key Exchange standard IKEv2.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] These third-generation documents standardized the abbreviation of IPsec to uppercase "IP" and lowercase "sec".
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] "ESP" generally refers to RFC 4303, which is the most recent version of the specification.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Since mid-2008, an IPsec Maintenance and Extensions (ipsecme) working group is active at the IETF.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In 2013, as part of the Snowden leaks, it was revealed that the US National Security Agency had been actively working to "Insert vulnerabilities into commercial encryption systems, IT systems, networks, and endpoint communications devices used by targets" as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] There are allegations that IPsec was a targeted encryption system.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The OpenBSD IPsec stack came later on and also was widely copied.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In a letter which OpenBSD lead developer Theo de Raadt received on 11 Dec 2010 from Gregory Perry, it is alleged that Jason Wright and others, working for the FBI, inserted "a number of backdoors and side channel key leaking mechanisms" into the OpenBSD crypto code.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In the forwarded email from 2010, Theo de Raadt did not at first express an official position on the validity of the claims, apart from the implicit endorsement from forwarding the email.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Jason Wright's response to the allegations: "Every urban legend is made more real by the inclusion of real names, dates, and times.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Gregory Perry's email falls into this category. ...
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] I will state clearly that I did not add backdoors to the OpenBSD operating system or the OpenBSD Cryptographic Framework (OCF)." Some days later, de Raadt commented that "I believe that NETSEC was probably contracted to write backdoors as alleged. ...
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] If those were written, I don't believe they made it into our tree." This was published before the Snowden leaks.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] An alternative explanation put forward by the authors of the Logjam attack suggests that the NSA compromised IPsec VPNs by undermining the Diffie-Hellman algorithm used in the key exchange.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] In their paper, they allege the NSA specially built a computing cluster to precompute multiplicative subgroups for specific primes and generators, such as for the second Oakley group defined in RFC 2409.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] As of May 2015, 90% of addressable IPsec VPNs supported the second Oakley group as part of IKE.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] If an organization were to precompute this group, they could derive the keys being exchanged and decrypt traffic without inserting any software backdoors.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] The Cisco PIX and ASA firewalls had vulnerabilities that were used for wiretapping by the NSA.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] Furthermore, IPsec VPNs using "Aggressive Mode" settings send a hash of the PSK in the clear.
[src:cloud-vpn/ipsec] This can be and apparently is targeted by the NSA using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN allows peers to authenticate each other using pre-shared secret keys, certificates or username/password.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] When used in a multiclient-server configuration, it allows the server to release an authentication certificate for every client, using signatures and certificate authority.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It uses the OpenSSL encryption library extensively, as well as the TLS protocol, and contains many security and control features.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] As it uses a custom security protocol that utilizes SSL/TLS for key exchange.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It is capable of traversing network address translators (NATs) and firewalls.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has been ported and embedded on several systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] For example, DD-WRT has the OpenVPN server function.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] SoftEther VPN, a multi-protocol VPN server, also has an implementation of the OpenVPN protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It was written by James Yonan and is free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Additionally, commercial licenses are available.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN uses the OpenSSL library to provide encryption of both the data and control channels.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It lets OpenSSL do all the encryption and authentication work, allowing OpenVPN to use all the ciphers available in the OpenSSL package.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It can also use the HMAC packet authentication feature to add an additional layer of security to the connection (referred to as an "HMAC Firewall" by the creator).
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It can also use hardware acceleration to get better encryption performance.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Support for mbed TLS is available starting from version 2.3.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has several ways to authenticate peers with each other.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN offers pre-shared keys, certificate-based, and username/password-based authentication.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Preshared secret key is the easiest, and certificate-based is the most robust and feature-rich.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] In version 2.0, username/password authentications can be enabled, both with or without certificates.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] However, to make use of username/password authentications, OpenVPN depends on third-party modules.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN can run over User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports, multiplexing created SSL tunnels on a single TCP/UDP port (RFC 3948 for UDP).
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] From 2.3.x series on, OpenVPN fully supports IPv6 as a protocol of the virtual network inside a tunnel and the OpenVPN applications can also establish connections via IPv6.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It has the ability to work through most proxy servers (including HTTP) and is good at working through network address translation (NAT) and getting out through firewalls.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] The server configuration can "push" certain network configuration options to the clients.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] These include IP addresses, routing commands, and a few connection options.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN offers two types of interfaces for networking via the Universal TUN/TAP driver.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It can create either a layer-3 based IP tunnel (TUN), or a layer-2 based Ethernet TAP that can carry any type of Ethernet traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN can optionally use the LZO compression library to compress the data stream.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Port 1194 is the official IANA assigned port number for OpenVPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Newer versions of the program now default to that port.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] A feature in the 2.0 version allows for one process to manage several simultaneous tunnels, as opposed to the original "one tunnel per process" restriction on the 1.x series.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN's use of common network protocols (TCP and UDP) makes it a desirable alternative to IPsec in situations where an ISP may block specific VPN protocols in order to force users to subscribe to a higher-priced, "business grade" service tier.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] For example, Comcast previously declared that their @Home product was, and had always been, designated as a residential service and did not allow the use of commercial applications.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Their argument was that conducting remote work via a VPN can adversely affect the network performance of their regular residential subscribers.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] They offered an alternative, @Home Professional, which would cost more than the @Home product.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] So, anyone wishing to use a VPN would have to subscribe to a higher-priced, business-grade service tier.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] When OpenVPN uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports to establish a tunnel, performance will be acceptable only as long as there is sufficient excess bandwidth on the un-tunneled network link to guarantee that the tunneled TCP timers do not expire.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] If this becomes untrue, performance falls off dramatically due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN offers various internal security features.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It has up to 256-bit encryption through the OpenSSL library, although some service providers may offer lower rates, effectively providing some of the fastest VPN available to consumers.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN also supports Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS), which regenerates encryption keys at set intervals, ensuring that even if one key is compromised, previous and future data remains secure.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Additionally, OpenVPN can be configured with various encryption ciphers, such as ChaCha20 and AES-256.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It runs in userspace instead of requiring IP stack (therefore kernel) operation.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has the ability to drop root privileges, use mlockall to prevent swapping sensitive data to disk, enter a chroot jail after initialization, and apply a SELinux context after initialization.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN runs a custom security protocol based on SSL and TLS, rather than supporting IKE, IPsec, L2TP or PPTP.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN supports the use of smart cards via PKCS#11-based cryptographic tokens.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN can be extended with third-party plug-ins or scripts, which can be called at defined entry points.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] The purpose of this is often to extend OpenVPN with more advanced logging, enhanced authentication with username and passwords, dynamic firewall updates, RADIUS integration and so on.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] The plug-ins are dynamically loadable modules, usually written in C, while the scripts interface can execute any scripts or binaries available to OpenVPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] In the OpenVPN source code there are some examples of such plug-ins, including a PAM authentication plug-in.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Several third-party plug-ins also exist to authenticate against LDAP or SQL databases such as SQLite and MySQL.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] This is an example for an OpenVPN control channel packet when HMAC based auth is enabled (tls-auth option in OpenVPN).
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] Data channel packets, which carry IP traffic, have a different format.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It is available on Solaris, Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, QNX, macOS and Windows XP and later.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN is available for mobile operating systems including Maemo, Windows Mobile 6.5 and below, iOS 3GS+ devices, jailbroken iOS 3.1.2+ devices, Android 4.0+ devices, and Android devices that have had the Cyanogenmod aftermarket firmware flashed or have the correct kernel module installed.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It is not compatible with some mobile phone OSes, including Palm OS.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] It is not a "web-based" VPN shown as a web page such as Citrix or Terminal Services Web access; the program is installed independently and configured by editing text files manually, rather than through a GUI-based wizard.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN is not compatible with VPN clients that use the IPsec over L2TP or PPTP protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] The entire package consists of one binary for both client and server connections, an optional configuration file, and one or more key files depending on the authentication method used.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into several router firmware packages allowing users to run OpenVPN in client or server mode from their network routers.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] A router running OpenVPN in client mode, for example, allows any device on a network to access a VPN without needing the capability to install OpenVPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has also been implemented in some manufacturer router firmware.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into SoftEther VPN, an open-source multi-protocol VPN server, to allow users to connect to the VPN server from existing OpenVPN clients.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN is also integrated into Vyos, an open-source routing operating system forked from the Vyatta software router.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] OpenVPN connections can be easily detected using deep packet inspection, based on known header data of the transmitted packets, regardless of the protocol or port used.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] While deep packet inspection does not allow determining the contents of the encrypted tunnel, it can be used to block the connection, identify communication participants, and log related data.
[src:cloud-vpn/openvpn] This is particularly important when the use of VPN connections is prohibited in certain environments, for example, in countries where encrypted connections are banned, or under civil legislation when circumventing network blocks in corporate networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:cloud-vpn/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In computer networks, a **tunneling protocol** is a communication protocol that allows for the movement of data from one network to another.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] They can, for example, allow private communications to be sent across a public network (such as the Internet), or for one network protocol to be carried over an incompatible network, through a process called encapsulation.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Because tunneling involves repackaging the traffic data into a different form, perhaps with encryption as standard, it can hide the nature of the traffic that is run through a tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling protocols work by using the data portion of a packet (the payload) to carry the packets that actually provide the service.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling uses a layered protocol model such as those of the OSI or TCP/IP protocol suite, but usually violates the layering when using the payload to carry a service not normally provided by the network.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Typically, the delivery protocol operates at an equal or higher level in the layered model than the payload protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] A tunneling protocol may, for example, allow a foreign protocol to run over a network that does not support that particular protocol, such as running IPv6 over IPv4.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Another important use is to provide services that are impractical or unsafe to be offered using only the underlying network services, such as providing a corporate network address to a remote user whose physical network address is not part of the corporate network.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Users can also use tunneling to "sneak through" a firewall, using a protocol that the firewall would normally block, but "wrapped" inside a protocol that the firewall does not block, such as HTTP.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] If the firewall policy does not specifically exclude this kind of "wrapping", this trick can function to get around the intended firewall policy (or any set of interlocked firewall policies).
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Another HTTP-based tunneling method uses the HTTP CONNECT method/command.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] A client issues the HTTP CONNECT command to an HTTP proxy.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The proxy then makes a TCP connection to a particular server:port, and relays data between that server:port and the client connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Because this creates a security hole, CONNECT-capable HTTP proxies commonly restrict access to the CONNECT method.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The proxy allows connections only to specific ports, such as 443 for HTTPS.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Other tunneling methods able to bypass network firewalls make use of different protocols such as DNS, MQTT, and SMS.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] As an example of network layer over network layer, Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE), a protocol running over IP (IP protocol number 47), often serves to carry IP packets, with RFC 1918 private addresses, over the Internet using delivery packets with public IP addresses.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In this case, the delivery and payload protocols are the same, but the payload addresses are incompatible with those of the delivery network.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] It is also possible to establish a connection using the data link layer.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) allows the transmission of frames between two nodes.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] A tunnel is not encrypted by default: the TCP/IP protocol chosen determines the level of security.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] SSH uses port 22 to enable data encryption of payloads being transmitted over a public network (such as the Internet) connection, thereby providing VPN functionality.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] IPsec has an end-to-end Transport Mode, but can also operate in a tunneling mode through a trusted security gateway.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] To understand a particular protocol stack imposed by tunneling, network engineers must understand both the payload and delivery protocol sets.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The throughput of a TCP‑over‑TCP connection can be degraded because the control loops in the inner and outer TCPs interfere destructively with each other.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Because TCP is designed to guarantee in‑order and complete packet delivery, the outer TCP masks the connection's health from the inner TCP.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In normal TCP operation, packet loss is detected when the receiver replies with duplicate ACKs to a packet received before the missing packet in the sequence.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In response, the sender retransmits the lost packet and halves the Congestion Window (CWND).
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In TCP‑over‑TCP, the outer TCP handles lost packets normally through retransmission and CWND reduction.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Still, since the inner TCP has not received any information indicating latency in the connection, it continues to transmit packets at the rate currently governed by its CWND.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP’s CWND is greater than the outer TCP’s, the outer TCP’s send buffer eventually fills.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] As the buffer inflates, packets experience longer and more variable queueing delays before transmission, thereby increasing the outer TCP’s measured round-trip time (RTT) and RTT variability.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] This inflates its retransmission timeout (RTO).
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Once the send buffer becomes full, the tunnel process can no longer forward inner‑TCP ACKs, so the inner TCP stops receiving acknowledgments entirely.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP is no longer receiving ACKs, its RTO expires, causing it to retransmit the oldest unacknowledged segment and double its RTO.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The inner TCP’s RTO then grows exponentially because it doubles with every timeout, and no ACKs are received to reset it.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] The result of a TCP meltdown is an outer TCP with a severely reduced CWND, an inflated RTO, and a full send buffer.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] This indicates that the inner TCP cannot write and that ACKs are not being sent in either direction.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] A *Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel* consists of an encrypted tunnel created through an SSH protocol connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Users may set up SSH tunnels to transfer unencrypted traffic over a network through an encrypted channel.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] It is a software-based approach to network security and the result is transparent encryption.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] For example, Microsoft Windows machines can share files using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol, a non-encrypted protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] If one were to mount a Microsoft Windows file-system remotely through the Internet, someone snooping on the connection could see transferred files.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] To mount the Windows file-system securely, one can establish a SSH tunnel that routes all SMB traffic to the remote fileserver through an encrypted channel.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Even though the SMB protocol itself contains no encryption, the encrypted SSH channel through which it travels offers security.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Once an SSH connection has been established, the tunnel starts with SSH listening to a port on the remote or local host.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Any connections to it are forwarded to the specified address and port originating from the opposing (remote or local, as previously) host.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Naturally, this wrapping and unwrapping also occurs in the reverse direction of the bidirectional tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] SSH tunnels provide a means to bypass firewalls that prohibit certain Internet services – so long as a site allows outgoing connections.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] For example, an organization may prohibit a user from accessing Internet web pages (port 80) directly without passing through the organization's proxy filter (which provides the organization with a means of monitoring and controlling what the user sees through the web).
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] But users may not wish to have their web traffic monitored or blocked by the organisation's proxy filter.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] If users can connect to an external SSH server, they can create an SSH tunnel to forward a given port on their local machine to port 80 on a remote web server.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Some SSH clients support dynamic port forwarding that allows the user to create a SOCKS 4/5 proxy.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In this case users can configure their applications to use their local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] This gives more flexibility than creating an SSH tunnel to a single port as previously described.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] SOCKS can free the user from the limitations of connecting only to a predefined remote port and server.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] If an application does not support SOCKS, a proxifier can be used to redirect the application to the local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Some proxifiers, such as Proxycap, support SSH directly, thus avoiding the need for an SSH client.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In recent versions of OpenSSH it is even allowed to create layer 2 or layer 3 tunnels if both ends have enabled such tunneling capabilities.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] This creates `tun` (layer 3, default) or `tap` (layer 2) virtual interfaces on both ends of the connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] This allows normal network management and routing to be used, and when used on routers, the traffic for an entire subnetwork can be tunneled.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] A pair of `tap` virtual interfaces function like an Ethernet cable connecting both ends of the connection and can join kernel bridges.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] Over the years, tunneling and data encapsulation have in very rare cases been adopted for malicious reasons, in order to maliciously communicate outside of a protected network.
[src:cloud-vpn/tunneling-protocol] In this context, known tunnels involve protocols such as HTTP, SSH, DNS, MQTT.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A **virtual private network** (**VPN**) is an overlay network that uses network virtualization to extend a private network across a public network, such as the Internet, via the use of encryption and tunneling protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In a VPN, a tunneling protocol is used to transfer network messages from one network host to another.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Host-to-network VPNs are commonly used by organizations to allow off-site users secure access to an office network over the Internet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs connect two networks, such as an office network and a datacenter.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Provider-provisioned VPNs isolate parts of the provider's own network infrastructure in virtual segments, in ways that make the contents of each segment private with respect to the others.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Individuals also use VPNs to encrypt and attempt to anonymize their network traffic, with VPN services selling access to their own private networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] However, the VPN provider and the online service being accessed via the VPN may have visibility of the user's activities.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful external data sniffing attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A network is a group of communicating computers known as hosts, which communicate data to other hosts via communication protocols, as facilitated by networking hardware.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Within a computer network, computers are identified by network addresses, which allow rule-based systems such as Internet Protocol (IP) to locate and identify hosts.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Hosts may also have hostnames, memorable labels for the host nodes, which are rarely changed after initial assignment.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The transmission medium that supports information exchange includes wired media like copper cables, optical fibers, and wireless radio-frequency media.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The arrangement of hosts and hardware within a network architecture is known as the network topology.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A communication protocol is a set of rules for exchanging information over a network.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Communication protocols have various characteristics, such as being connection-oriented or connectionless, or using circuit switching or packet switching.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In a protocol stack, often constructed per the OSI model, communications functions are divided into protocol layers, where each layer leverages the services of the layer below it until the lowest layer controls the hardware that sends information across the media.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The use of protocol layering is ubiquitous across the field of computer networking.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] An important example of a protocol stack is HTTP, the World Wide Web protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] HTTP runs over TCP over IP, the internet protocols, which in turn run over IEEE 802.11, the Wi-Fi protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This stack is used between a wireless router and a personal computer when accessing the web.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Most modern computer networks use protocols based on packet-mode transmission.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A network packet is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Packets consist of two types of data: control information and user data (payload).
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The control information provides data the network needs to deliver the user data, for example, source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, and sequencing information.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers, with payload data in between.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The Internet protocol suite, also called TCP/IP, is the foundation of all modern networking and the defining set of protocols for the Internet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] It offers connection-less and connection-oriented services over an inherently unreliable network traversed by datagram transmission using Internet protocol (IP).
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] At its core, the protocol suite defines the addressing, identification, and routing specifications for Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) and for IPv6, the next generation of the protocol with a much enlarged addressing capability.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] VPNs do not make connected users anonymous or unidentifiable to the untrusted medium network provider, such as an Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] However, VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful data sniffing attacks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Data packets travelling across a VPN may also be secured by tamper proofing via a message authentication code, prevents the message from being altered or tampered without being rejected, enhancing data integrity.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A number of other implementations exist to ensure authentication of connecting parties.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Tunnel endpoints can be authenticated in various ways during the VPN access initiation, such as by the whitelisting of endpoint IP address.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Authentication may also occur after actual tunnels are already active, for example, with a web captive portal.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Remote-access VPNs may also use passwords, biometrics, two-factor authentication, or other cryptographic methods.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs often use passwords (pre-shared keys) or digital certificates.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This connection state is usually facilitated through the simultaneous use of a LAN network interface controller (NIC), radio NIC, Wireless LAN NIC, and virtual private network client software application.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling is most commonly configured via the use of a remote-access VPN client, which allows the user to simultaneously connect to a nearby wireless network, resources on an off-site corporate network, as well as websites over the Internet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Advantages of split tunneling include alleviating bottlenecks, conserving bandwidth (as Internet traffic does not have to pass through the VPN server), and enabling a user to not have to continually connect and disconnect when remotely accessing resources..
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Disadvantages include DNS leaks and potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Internet service providers often use split tunneling to that implement for DNS hijacking purposes.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A *host-to-network* configuration is analogous to joining one or more computers to a network to which they cannot be directly connected.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This type of extension provides computer access to a local area network of a remote site, or any wider enterprise networks, such as an intranet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Each computer is in charge of activating its own tunnel towards the network it wants to join.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The joined network is only aware of a single remote host for each tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This may be employed for remote workers, or to enable people accessing their private home or company resources without exposing them on the public Internet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A *site-to-site* configuration connects two networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This configuration expands a network across geographically disparate locations.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Tunneling is only done between gateway devices located at each network location.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] These devices then make the tunnel available to other local network hosts that aim to reach any host on the other side.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This is useful to keep sites connected to each other in a stable manner, like office networks to their headquarters or datacenter.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In this case, any side may be configured to initiate the communication as long as it knows how to reach the other.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In the context of site-to-site configurations, the terms *intranet* and *extranet* are used to describe two different use cases.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] An *intranet* site-to-site VPN describes a configuration where the sites connected by the VPN belong to the same organization, whereas an *extranet* site-to-site VPN joins sites belonging to multiple organizations.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support broadcast domains.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Therefore, communication, software, and networking that are based on layer 2 and broadcast packets (such as NetBIOS used in Windows networking) may not be fully supported as on a local area network.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Variants on VPN such as Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Trusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead, they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) often overlays trusted VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A secure VPN either trusts the underlying delivery network or enforces security with an internal mechanism.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Mobile VPNs are widely used in public safety where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as computer-assisted dispatch and criminal databases, and in other organizations with similar requirements such as field service management and healthcare.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network (DMVPN) is a dynamic tunneling form of a virtual private network supported on Cisco IOS-based routers, Huawei AR G3 routers, and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] DMVPN provides the capability for creating a dynamic-mesh VPN network without having to statically pre-configure all possible tunnel end-point peers, such as IPsec and ISAKMP peers.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] DMVPN is initially configured to build a hub-and-spoke network by statically configuring the hubs (VPN headends) on the spokes; no change in the configuration on the hub is required to accept new spokes.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Using this initial hub-and-spoke network, tunnels between spokes are dynamically built on demand without additional configuration on the hubs or spokes.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This dynamic-mesh capability alleviates the need for any load on the hub to route data between the spoke networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) is a technology for carrying OSI layer 2 Ethernet traffic as a virtual private network using wide area network protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a routing technique in telecommunications networks that directs data from one node to the next based on labels rather than network addresses.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Whereas network addresses identify endpoints, MPLS labels identify established paths between endpoints.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] MPLS can encapsulate packets of various network protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service Ethernet traffic.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) is a virtual private network technology that provides Ethernet-based multipoint-to-multipoint communication over IP or MPLS networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] It allows geographically dispersed sites to share an Ethernet broadcast domain by connecting sites (including both servers and clients) through pseudowires.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The technologies that can be used as pseudo-wire can be Ethernet over MPLS, L2TPv3 or even GRE.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] There are two IETF standards-track RFCs (RFC 4761 and RFC 4762) describing VPLS establishment.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In contrast to L2TPv3, which allows only point-to-point OSI layer 2 tunnels, VPLS allows any-to-any (multipoint) connectivity.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A virtual private network is based on a tunneling protocol, and may be combined with other network or application protocols to provide additional security and capabilities.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) is a standards-based security protocol, initially developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for IPv6, and was required in all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The design of IPSec meets most security goals: availability, integrity, and confidentiality.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] IPsec is also often supported by network hardware accelerators, which makes IPsec VPN desirable for low-power scenarios, like always-on remote access VPN configurations.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels are set up by the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels made with IKE version 1 (also known as IKEv1 tunnels, or often just "IPsec tunnels") can be used alone to provide VPN but are often combined with the Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) to reuse existing L2TP-related implementations for more flexible authentication features (e.g.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] IKE version 2, which was created by Microsoft and Cisco, can be used alone to provide IPsec VPN functionality.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Its primary advantages are the native support for authenticating via the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) and that the tunnel can be seamlessly restored when the IP address of the associated host is changing, which is typical of a roaming mobile device, whether on 3G or 4G LTE networks.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the OpenVPN project and SoftEther VPN project) or secure an individual connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through TLS.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] A VPN based on TLS can connect from locations where the usual TLS web navigation (HTTPS) is supported without requiring additional configuration.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH offers VPN tunneling (distinct from port forwarding) to secure remote connections to a network, inter-network links, and remote systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] SSH is more often used to remotely connect to machines or networks instead of a site to site VPN connection.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] OpenVPN is a free and open-source VPN protocol based on the TLS protocol.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] It supports perfect forward-secrecy, and most modern secure cipher suites, like AES, Serpent, TwoFish, etc.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] It is currently being developed and updated by OpenVPN Inc., a non-profit providing secure VPN technologies.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) is a form of VPN tunnel that provides a mechanism to transport Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an SSL/TLS channel.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] WireGuard is a protocol designed to be more lightweight than OpenVPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In 2020, WireGuard support was added to both the Linux and Android kernels, opening it up to adoption by VPN providers.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] By default, WireGuard utilizes the Curve25519 protocol for key exchange and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption and message authentication, but also includes the ability to pre-share a symmetric key between the client and server.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Desktop, smartphone and other end-user device operating systems usually support configuring remote access VPN from their graphical or command-line tools.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] However, due to the variety of, often non standard, VPN protocols, there exist many third-party applications that implement additional protocols not yet or no longer natively supported by the OS.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] For instance, Android lacked native IPsec IKEv2 support until version 11, and users needed to install third-party apps in order to connect that kind of VPN.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Conversely, Windows does not natively support plain IPsec IKEv1 remote access native VPN configuration (commonly used by Cisco and Fritz!Box VPN solutions).
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Network appliances, such as firewalls, often include VPN gateway functionality for either remote access or site-to-site configurations.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Their administration interfaces often facilitate setting up virtual private networks with a selection of supported protocols.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In some cases, like in the open source operating systems devoted to firewalls and network devices (like OpenWrt, IPFire, PfSense or OPNsense), it is possible to add support for additional VPN protocols by installing missing software components or third-party apps.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Commercial appliances with VPN features based on proprietary hardware or software platforms usually support a consistent VPN protocol across their products, but do not allow customizations outside the use cases they implement.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] This is often the case for appliances that rely on hardware acceleration of VPNs to provide higher throughput or support a larger number of simultaneously connected users.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] According to a 2022 estimate, 3% of Chinese netizens use VPNs, compared to 8.5% of Americans.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] In China, VPNs are increasingly blocked and unauthorized usage can be subject to fines and legal prosecution.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Based on its estimates of leaked government documents, ChinaFile estimated in 2026 that VPN demand in China was in the low single digits.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] It also estimated that foreign apps blocked by the Great Firewall have extremely low traffic, particularly compared to domestic apps; the top five domestic apps saw traffic that was 1,000 times more than the top five foreign apps.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] As of 2025, approximately 1.75 billion people used VPNs.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] By 2027, this market is projected to grow to $76 billion.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] Amid Internet restrictions and blocking in Russia, Internet activists created the Amnezia VPN project in 2020 during a digital rights hackathon organized by Roskomsvoboda.
[src:cloud-vpn/virtual-private-network] The service gained popularity among Russian users by providing access to blocked resources, as well as features aimed at enhancing anonymity and resistance to traffic analysis.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In March 2020, the Linux version of the software reached a stable production release and was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 kernel, and backported to earlier Linux kernels in some Linux distributions.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The Linux kernel components are licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 2; other implementations are under GPLv2 or other free/open-source licenses.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The WireGuard protocol is a variant of the Noise Protocol Framework `IK` handshake pattern.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The key exchange, or handshake, combines long-term and ephemeral Diffie-Hellman values using Curve25519.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Each pair generates a set of public and private key pairs using Curve 25519, the public keys are exchanged, with each pair then assigned an IP address (generally RFC 1918) to utilize with the WireGuard tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Once the keys have been confirmed by both peers, the Noise Protocol is used to generate a shared ChaCha20 session key for symmetric encryption authenticated with Poly1305.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] SipHash24 is used for hashtable keys while BLAKE2s cryptographic hash functions, a faster and more compact version of SHA-3, are incorporated.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Key derivation functions are handled using HKDF and Base64-encoded private keys, public keys and preshared keys.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard’s proof starts by modeling its two-message Noise-based handshake (plus optional PSK) in CryptoVerif’s calculus of cryptographic games, abstracting ChaCha20-Poly1305, Curve25519, HKDF, the hash chain, and related primitives under standard IND-CPA/INT-CTXT and random-oracle assumptions.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] From that model, CryptoVerif’s automated game hops show, across unlimited parallel sessions, that the protocol guarantees mutual authentication, IND-CCA session-key secrecy, forward secrecy and post-compromise security even if long-term keys later leak and state is wiped.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In May 2019, researchers from INRIA published a machine-checked proof of the WireGuard protocol, produced using the CryptoVerif proof assistant.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard supports pre-shared symmetric key mode, which provides an additional layer of symmetric encryption to mitigate future advances in quantum computing.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] This addresses the risk that traffic may be stored until quantum computers are capable of breaking Curve25519, at which point traffic could be decrypted.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Pre-shared keys are "usually troublesome from a key management perspective and might be more likely stolen", but in the shorter term, if the symmetric key is compromised, the Curve25519 keys still provide more than sufficient protection.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard uses only UDP, due to the potential disadvantages of TCP-over-TCP.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Tunneling TCP over a TCP-based connection can induce a dramatic loss in transmission performance due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard fully supports IPv6, both inside and outside of tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] It supports only layer 3 for both IPv4 and IPv6 and can encapsulate v4-in-v6 and vice versa.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Assuming the underlay network transporting the WireGuard packets maintains a 1500 byte MTU, configuring the WireGuard interface to 1420 bytes MTU for all involved peers is ideal for being transported over IPv6 + IPv4.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] However, when exclusively utilizing legacy IPv4 transport, a higher MTU of 1440 bytes for the WireGuard interface suffices.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] From an operational perspective and for network configuration uniformity, leaving the default 1420 byte MTU network-wide for the WireGuard interfaces would be advantageous.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] This approach ensures consistency and facilitates a smoother transition to enabling IPv6 for the WireGuard peers and interfaces in the future.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Hosts often avoid sending packets > 1280 due to PMTUD reliability.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The MTU of a WireGuard interface is determined by the encapsulating, or *outer*, IP protocol—not the IP version carried inside the tunnel.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] When WireGuard packets are transported over IPv4, the outer-header overhead is 60 bytes (20-byte IPv4 header, 8-byte UDP header, and 32-byte WireGuard header).
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] When transported over IPv6, the outer-header overhead rises to 80 bytes.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] This distinction means that even if a peer is reachable only via IPv4, other peers in the same mesh may connect over IPv6 or through translation mechanisms.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Translation increases header size and enforces IPv6’s 1280-byte minimum path MTU, requiring that implementers budget for the 80-byte IPv6 overhead when setting a consistent interface MTU.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard is designed to be extended by third-party programs and scripts.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] This has been used to augment WireGuard with various features including more user-friendly management interfaces (including easier setting up of keys), logging, dynamic firewall updates, dynamic IP assignment, and LDAP integration.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] It is supported natively and by a number of commercial VPN services such as NordVPN, IPVanish, Mullvad, and TunnelBear.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] One WireGuard-based fork, AmneziaWG, adds traffic-obfuscation mechanisms intended to make WireGuard traffic less identifiable to deep packet inspection systems.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Excluding such complex features from the minimal core codebase improves its stability and security.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] For ensuring security, WireGuard restricts the options for implementing cryptographic controls, limits the choices for key exchange processes, and maps algorithms to a small subset of modern cryptographic primitives.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] If a flaw is found in any of the primitives, a new version can be released that resolves the issue.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] A review by *Ars Technica* found that WireGuard was easy to set up and use, used strong ciphers, and had a minimal codebase that provided for a small attack surface.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] A 2024 report concluded that WireGuard had potential as a lightweight robust solution for Internet of things security.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] WireGuard has received funding from the Open Technology Fund and donations from *Jump Trading*, Mullvad, Tailscale, *Fly.io*, and the NLnet Foundation.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Oregon senator Ron Wyden has recommended to the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) that they evaluate WireGuard as a replacement for existing technologies.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Early snapshots of the code base exist from 30 June 2016.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The logo is inspired by a stone engraving of the mythological Python that Jason Donenfeld saw while visiting a museum in Delphi.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 9 December 2019, David Miller – primary maintainer of the Linux networking stack – accepted the WireGuard patches into the "net-next" maintainer tree, for inclusion in an upcoming kernel.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 28 January 2020, Linus Torvalds merged David Miller's net-next tree, and WireGuard entered the mainline Linux kernel tree.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 20 March 2020, Debian developers enabled the module build options for WireGuard in their kernel config for the Debian 11 version (testing).
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 29 March 2020 WireGuard was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 release tree.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The Windows version of the software remains at beta.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] This led to Android developers adding native kernel support for WireGuard in their Generic Kernel Image on 30 March 2020.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 22 April 2020, NetworkManager developer Beniamino Galvani merged GUI support for WireGuard in GNOME.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 12 May 2020, Matt Dunwoodie proposed patches for native kernel support of WireGuard in OpenBSD.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 22 June 2020, after the work of Matt Dunwoodie and Jason A.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Donenfeld, WireGuard support was imported into OpenBSD.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Donenfeld released an update of the Windows package improving installation, stability, ARM support, and enterprise features.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 29 November 2020, WireGuard support was imported into the FreeBSD 13 kernel.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] On 19 January 2021, WireGuard support was added for preview in pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 development snapshots.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In March 2021, kernel-mode WireGuard support was removed from FreeBSD 13.0, still in testing, after an urgent code cleanup in FreeBSD WireGuard could not be completed quickly.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] FreeBSD-based pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 and pfSense Plus 21.02 removed kernel-based WireGuard as well.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In May 2021, WireGuard support was re-introduced back into pfSense CE and pfSense Plus development snapshots as an experimental package written by a member of the pfSense community, Christian McDonald.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] The WireGuard package for pfSense incorporates the ongoing kernel-mode WireGuard development work by Jason A.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] Donenfeld that was originally sponsored by Netgate.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In June 2021, the official package repositories for both pfSense CE 2.5.2 and pfSense Plus 21.05 included the WireGuard package.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In 2023, WireGuard received over 209,000€ support from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In June 2025, IPFire has added support for WireGuard using the Linux kernel implementation.
[src:cloud-vpn/wireguard] In January 2026 Iran International reported that WireGuard was being used in Iran in the aftermath of the 2026 Iran protests, albeit with limited success.
